1
00:04:09,457 --> 00:04:11,764
- It's getting cold.
- Thanks.

2
00:04:15,550 --> 00:04:17,378
That is one fine frame.

3
00:04:19,055 --> 00:04:20,831
One fine frame, that is.

4
00:04:22,732 --> 00:04:23,854
How much...

5
00:04:26,475 --> 00:04:30,935
...does a fine frame
like that cost, do you think?

6
00:04:32,521 --> 00:04:33,700
I never told you,

7
00:04:33,700 --> 00:04:36,833
but you sound a little like
Dr. Seuss when you're drunk.

8
00:04:36,964 --> 00:04:38,879
Anna, I'm serious.

9
00:04:40,334 --> 00:04:41,738
Serious, I am, Anna.

10
00:04:44,494 --> 00:04:47,323
I'd say it cost
at least a couple hundred.

11
00:04:48,062 --> 00:04:49,673
I'm gonna read it for you.

12
00:04:49,804 --> 00:04:51,604
Do I really sound
like Dr. Seuss?

13
00:04:51,604 --> 00:04:54,635
"In recognition of his
outstanding achievement

14
00:04:54,765 --> 00:04:57,198
in the field
of child psychology,

15
00:04:57,285 --> 00:04:59,074
his dedication to his work

16
00:04:59,204 --> 00:05:02,730
and his continuing efforts to
improve the quality of life..."

17
00:05:03,343 --> 00:05:05,347
Will you concentrate?

18
00:05:06,093 --> 00:05:09,487
"...his continuing efforts
to improve the quality of life

19
00:05:09,487 --> 00:05:11,923
for countless children
and their families,

20
00:05:12,526 --> 00:05:16,528
the city of Philadelphia
proudly bestows upon its son,

21
00:05:16,528 --> 00:05:19,008
Dr. Malcolm Crowe..."
That's you.

22
00:05:19,246 --> 00:05:22,620
"...the Mayor's Citation
for Professional Excellence."

23
00:05:24,100 --> 00:05:25,944
They called you their son.

24
00:05:27,146 --> 00:05:28,225
Wow.

25
00:05:29,957 --> 00:05:31,820
We should hang it
in the bathroom.

26
00:05:35,591 --> 00:05:38,028
This is an important
night for us.

27
00:05:39,720 --> 00:05:43,706
Finally, someone is recognizing
the sacrifices you've made.

28
00:05:44,077 --> 00:05:47,390
That you have put everything
second, including me...

29
00:05:48,702 --> 00:05:51,694
...for those families
that they're talking about.

30
00:05:55,612 --> 00:05:58,521
They're also saying
that my husband has a gift.

31
00:06:00,108 --> 00:06:03,360
You have a gift that teaches
children how to be strong

32
00:06:03,360 --> 00:06:07,883
in situations where most adults
would piss on themselves.

33
00:06:08,712 --> 00:06:11,540
I believe what
they wrote is real.

34
00:06:15,589 --> 00:06:16,720
Thank you.

35
00:06:21,247 --> 00:06:23,902
I would like
some wine in a glass.

36
00:06:24,032 --> 00:06:27,993
I would not like it in a mug.
I would not like it in a jug.

37
00:06:53,070 --> 00:06:54,113
Look.

38
00:07:37,848 --> 00:07:40,764
Anna, don't move.
Don't make a sound.

39
00:07:45,160 --> 00:07:47,206
This is 47 Locust Street.

40
00:07:49,753 --> 00:07:52,147
You've broken a window
and entered a private residence.

41
00:07:52,147 --> 00:07:53,961
You don't know so many things.

42
00:07:56,553 --> 00:07:57,608
There are no needles

43
00:07:57,608 --> 00:08:00,176
or prescription drugs
of any kind in this house.

44
00:08:09,881 --> 00:08:12,755
Do you know why you're
afraid when you're alone?

45
00:08:15,485 --> 00:08:17,934
I do. I do.

46
00:08:19,422 --> 00:08:20,891
What do you want?

47
00:08:20,891 --> 00:08:22,939
What he promised me!

48
00:08:23,186 --> 00:08:26,173
- I want what he promised me.
- Oh, my God.

49
00:08:26,854 --> 00:08:27,950
Do I know you?

50
00:08:27,950 --> 00:08:29,989
Don't you know me, hero?

51
00:08:31,101 --> 00:08:33,559
Don't you even remember
your own patients?

52
00:08:36,867 --> 00:08:39,280
D... Downtown clinic.

53
00:08:39,625 --> 00:08:42,742
S... Single-parent family.

54
00:08:44,700 --> 00:08:46,572
Possible mood disorder.

55
00:08:48,269 --> 00:08:50,399
I was afraid!

56
00:08:50,924 --> 00:08:54,698
You told me I was having trouble
coping with my parents' divorce.

57
00:08:54,698 --> 00:08:58,546
You... You were wrong.
You were wrong.

58
00:09:01,046 --> 00:09:02,891
Now look at me!

59
00:09:04,346 --> 00:09:06,198
I don't want
to be afraid no more.

60
00:09:06,198 --> 00:09:08,046
Please, just give me
a minute to think.

61
00:09:08,046 --> 00:09:10,945
I waited ten years for you!

62
00:09:11,076 --> 00:09:12,913
I'm not giving you nothing!

63
00:09:13,626 --> 00:09:15,026
Ben Friedkin?

64
00:09:15,376 --> 00:09:18,867
Some people,
they call me "freak".

65
00:09:20,363 --> 00:09:21,685
Ronald Sumner?

66
00:09:22,131 --> 00:09:25,462
I am. I am a freak.
Look at...

67
00:09:26,637 --> 00:09:27,755
Vincent.

68
00:09:29,673 --> 00:09:30,909
Vincent Grey.

69
00:09:34,470 --> 00:09:36,142
Don't. Don't.

70
00:09:36,142 --> 00:09:37,613
I do remember you.

71
00:09:39,217 --> 00:09:41,935
- No.
- Quiet, very smart.

72
00:09:43,240 --> 00:09:44,573
Compassionate.

73
00:09:45,982 --> 00:09:48,136
Unusually compassionate.

74
00:09:50,618 --> 00:09:52,622
You forgot "cursed".

75
00:09:55,949 --> 00:09:57,599
You failed me.

76
00:09:58,734 --> 00:10:00,954
You failed me!

77
00:10:04,305 --> 00:10:08,644
Vincent, I'm sorry if I
wasn't... if I didn't help you.

78
00:10:08,644 --> 00:10:11,628
But if you just...
let me try.

79
00:10:11,911 --> 00:10:13,598
You just
give me a chance...

80
00:10:21,372 --> 00:10:24,282
- Oh, God. Oh, God, honey.

81
00:10:24,413 --> 00:10:27,024
- Did Vincent...
- Now, don't talk. Shh.

82
00:12:45,015 --> 00:12:48,085
De profundis
clamo ad te, Domine.

83
00:12:49,913 --> 00:12:53,264
De profundis
clamo ad te, Domine.

84
00:12:57,877 --> 00:12:59,279
It's okay, Cole.

85
00:13:00,085 --> 00:13:02,168
My name is Dr. Malcolm Crowe.

86
00:13:03,709 --> 00:13:07,548
We were supposed to meet today,
but I missed our appointment.

87
00:13:07,846 --> 00:13:08,939
I'm sorry.

88
00:13:18,589 --> 00:13:20,776
You know,
in the olden days in Europe,

89
00:13:20,776 --> 00:13:22,947
people used to
hide out in churches.

90
00:13:23,365 --> 00:13:25,190
They would claim sanctuary.

91
00:13:30,727 --> 00:13:32,321
What were they hiding from?

92
00:13:36,179 --> 00:13:38,116
Bad people, mostly.

93
00:13:38,529 --> 00:13:43,009
People that wanted to put
them in jail... hurt them.

94
00:13:45,449 --> 00:13:49,008
Noticed your eyeglasses. They
don't have any lenses in them.

95
00:13:50,184 --> 00:13:51,792
They're my dad's.

96
00:13:52,217 --> 00:13:53,950
The lenses hurt my eyes.

97
00:13:55,668 --> 00:13:57,418
What were you talking
about with your soldiers

98
00:13:57,418 --> 00:13:58,849
when I came in?

99
00:13:59,464 --> 00:14:03,198
- De...
- De profundis clamo ad te, Domine.

100
00:14:04,788 --> 00:14:05,996
It's called "Latin".

101
00:14:10,583 --> 00:14:12,520
All your soldiers
speak Latin?

102
00:14:13,118 --> 00:14:14,177
No.

103
00:14:14,788 --> 00:14:15,922
Just one.

104
00:14:18,609 --> 00:14:20,518
A-Are you a good doctor?

105
00:14:21,562 --> 00:14:22,743
Well...

106
00:14:24,379 --> 00:14:25,660
I used to be.

107
00:14:27,406 --> 00:14:30,433
I won an award once
from the mayor.

108
00:14:31,627 --> 00:14:33,494
Had an
expensive frame.

109
00:14:48,158 --> 00:14:49,808
I'm gonna see you again, right?

110
00:14:50,430 --> 00:14:52,285
If that's okay with you.

111
00:15:27,022 --> 00:15:28,101
It's me.

112
00:17:15,605 --> 00:17:18,696
Pennsylvania Turnpike westbound
slow to Valley Forge 24.

113
00:17:18,696 --> 00:17:22,763
On the Blue Ridge both directions,
generally slow between number three...

114
00:17:24,895 --> 00:17:27,811
- Hey, good morning.

115
00:17:35,515 --> 00:17:36,622
Cole?

116
00:17:40,907 --> 00:17:42,127
Cole?

117
00:17:43,785 --> 00:17:46,020
Hey, your Cocoa Puffs
are getting soggy.

118
00:17:48,790 --> 00:17:52,489
Let me see you.
Aw, honey, you got a spot.

119
00:18:01,411 --> 00:18:03,457
Okay, here it comes.

120
00:18:16,819 --> 00:18:18,668
Something you were
looking for, baby?

121
00:18:21,867 --> 00:18:23,060
Pop-Tarts?

122
00:18:25,919 --> 00:18:27,011
They're right here.

123
00:18:29,230 --> 00:18:30,306
Oh.

124
00:18:37,362 --> 00:18:39,014
What are you
thinking, Mama?

125
00:18:41,453 --> 00:18:43,100
Lots of things.

126
00:18:44,950 --> 00:18:46,676
Anything bad about me?

127
00:18:46,980 --> 00:18:48,696
Hey, look at my face.

128
00:18:50,080 --> 00:18:52,650
I was not thinking
something bad about you.

129
00:18:54,052 --> 00:18:55,083
Got it?

130
00:18:58,253 --> 00:18:59,307
Got it.

131
00:19:01,518 --> 00:19:03,433
- Get up.

132
00:19:03,563 --> 00:19:05,631
- Th-That's Tommy, Mom.
- Okay, you tuck it in.

133
00:19:05,631 --> 00:19:08,329
Hey, Cole?
You want this?

134
00:19:38,731 --> 00:19:41,523
Hey, freak, how'd you like that
arm-around-the-shoulder bit?

135
00:19:42,213 --> 00:19:46,260
I just made that up. I went
with it as great actors do.

136
00:19:46,390 --> 00:19:47,603
It's called "improv".

137
00:20:26,389 --> 00:20:27,512
Hey, baby.

138
00:20:29,375 --> 00:20:30,915
How was your day?

139
00:20:32,632 --> 00:20:33,730
Hmm?

140
00:20:38,053 --> 00:20:40,376
You know, you can
tell me things if you need to.

141
00:20:45,975 --> 00:20:47,568
Oh, you know what I did today?

142
00:20:49,108 --> 00:20:53,678
I, uh... I won the Pennsylvania
Lottery in the morning.

143
00:20:55,056 --> 00:20:56,594
I quit my jobs.

144
00:20:56,594 --> 00:20:59,554
And I ate a big
picnic in the park

145
00:20:59,554 --> 00:21:01,223
with lots of
chocolate mousse pie.

146
00:21:01,706 --> 00:21:04,320
And then I swam
in the fountain all afternoon.

147
00:21:05,124 --> 00:21:06,183
What'd you do?

148
00:21:12,132 --> 00:21:15,051
I was picked first for
kickball teams at recess.

149
00:21:15,897 --> 00:21:17,921
I hit a grand slam
to win the game.

150
00:21:18,347 --> 00:21:21,642
Everybody lifted me up
and carried me around, cheering.

151
00:21:26,756 --> 00:21:29,976
In that case, I am gonna
make you some triangle pancakes.

152
00:21:30,848 --> 00:21:32,026
You got an hour.

153
00:21:38,709 --> 00:21:39,751
Hi.

154
00:21:45,676 --> 00:21:46,702
Want to sit?

155
00:21:51,738 --> 00:21:53,364
Don't feel like
talking today?

156
00:21:58,209 --> 00:21:59,627
Wanna play a game?

157
00:22:01,531 --> 00:22:02,914
It's
a mind-reading game.

158
00:22:03,779 --> 00:22:05,074
Here's how it works:

159
00:22:05,999 --> 00:22:07,195
I read your mind.

160
00:22:08,429 --> 00:22:11,764
If what I say is right, you
take one step towards the chair.

161
00:22:12,459 --> 00:22:14,066
If what
I say is wrong,

162
00:22:14,066 --> 00:22:17,069
you take one step back
towards the doorway.

163
00:22:17,897 --> 00:22:20,874
If you reach the chair,
you sit down.

164
00:22:21,540 --> 00:22:24,730
If you reach the door,
you can go.

165
00:22:26,906 --> 00:22:28,111
Wanna play?

166
00:22:36,742 --> 00:22:37,833
Okay.

167
00:22:53,791 --> 00:22:56,174
When your mother and father
were first divorced,

168
00:22:57,341 --> 00:23:01,318
your mom went to see a doctor
like me, and he didn't help her,

169
00:23:02,652 --> 00:23:05,001
so you think I'm not
going to be able to help you.

170
00:23:20,918 --> 00:23:24,577
You're worried that
she said she told him things,

171
00:23:25,612 --> 00:23:27,641
things she couldn't
tell anyone else.

172
00:23:29,323 --> 00:23:30,459
Secrets.

173
00:23:38,502 --> 00:23:40,786
You have a secret,
but you don't want to tell me.

174
00:23:54,565 --> 00:23:56,334
Your dad gave you
that watch as a present

175
00:23:56,334 --> 00:23:57,710
just before he went away.

176
00:24:09,104 --> 00:24:10,611
He forgot it in a drawer.

177
00:24:11,754 --> 00:24:12,911
Doesn't work.

178
00:24:25,435 --> 00:24:27,702
You keep pretty quiet
in school, but...

179
00:24:28,885 --> 00:24:30,474
...you're a good student.

180
00:24:30,855 --> 00:24:33,134
You've never really been
in any serious trouble.

181
00:24:41,046 --> 00:24:42,907
We were supposed
to draw a picture.

182
00:24:43,931 --> 00:24:45,326
Anything we wanted.

183
00:24:48,227 --> 00:24:49,528
I drew a man...

184
00:24:51,289 --> 00:24:54,172
...got hurt in the neck by
another man with a screwdriver.

185
00:24:57,933 --> 00:24:59,770
You saw that on TV, Cole?

186
00:25:04,817 --> 00:25:06,510
Everyone got upset.

187
00:25:07,617 --> 00:25:09,068
They had a meeting.

188
00:25:10,587 --> 00:25:12,167
Mom started crying.

189
00:25:13,317 --> 00:25:15,347
I don't draw
like that anymore.

190
00:25:17,126 --> 00:25:18,732
How do you draw now?

191
00:25:21,610 --> 00:25:24,374
Draw... people smiling...

192
00:25:25,028 --> 00:25:26,316
...dogs running...

193
00:25:28,478 --> 00:25:29,723
...rainbows.

194
00:25:31,478 --> 00:25:34,014
They don't have
meetings about rainbows.

195
00:25:35,738 --> 00:25:36,832
No.

196
00:25:37,823 --> 00:25:39,096
I guess they don't.

197
00:25:47,942 --> 00:25:49,654
What am I thinking now?

198
00:25:51,299 --> 00:25:53,283
I don't know
what you're thinking now.

199
00:26:00,868 --> 00:26:02,226
I was thinking,

200
00:26:02,782 --> 00:26:04,182
you're nice...

201
00:26:06,875 --> 00:26:08,515
...but you can't help me.

202
00:26:25,556 --> 00:26:26,995
I thought you meant
the other Italian restaurant

203
00:26:26,995 --> 00:26:28,418
I asked you
to marry me in.

204
00:26:36,166 --> 00:26:37,571
I'm so sorry, Anna.

205
00:26:39,311 --> 00:26:41,779
I just can't seem
to keep track of time.

206
00:26:44,881 --> 00:26:47,384
And I didn't have
a very good session today. I...

207
00:26:52,356 --> 00:26:53,994
They're both so similar.

208
00:26:55,202 --> 00:26:58,102
Same mannerisms,
same expressions, same...

209
00:26:58,232 --> 00:26:59,974
...things hanging
over their head.

210
00:27:03,063 --> 00:27:04,935
I think it might
be some kind of abuse.

211
00:27:06,722 --> 00:27:10,322
Cole has...
scratches on his arm.

212
00:27:10,322 --> 00:27:12,497
I think they might
be fingernail cuts.

213
00:27:12,832 --> 00:27:15,096
Defensive cuts, maybe.
I don't know, Anna.

214
00:27:17,731 --> 00:27:20,151
Maybe a teacher or a neighbor.

215
00:27:20,273 --> 00:27:23,043
I don't think it's the mother.
I've seen her with him, and...

216
00:27:23,563 --> 00:27:25,334
...doesn't seem to fit.

217
00:27:28,263 --> 00:27:29,944
Or I could just be wrong.

218
00:27:30,483 --> 00:27:33,175
Maybe he's just a kid who
likes to climb trees a lot.

219
00:27:41,984 --> 00:27:43,662
Anna...

220
00:27:45,544 --> 00:27:47,946
I know that I've been
a little distant. I...

221
00:27:49,285 --> 00:27:51,602
I know that it makes
you mad. I just...

222
00:27:52,085 --> 00:27:53,935
...feel like I'm being
given a second chance

223
00:27:53,935 --> 00:27:55,808
and I don't want
it to slip away.

224
00:27:58,024 --> 00:27:59,111
Anna.

225
00:28:01,168 --> 00:28:02,567
Happy anniversary.

226
00:28:12,918 --> 00:28:14,903
Stop looking at me.

227
00:28:15,312 --> 00:28:17,519
I don't like when people
look at me like that.

228
00:28:18,005 --> 00:28:19,029
Okay.

229
00:28:20,885 --> 00:28:23,796
I walk this way to school
with Tommy Tammisimo.

230
00:28:24,524 --> 00:28:25,840
He your best buddy?

231
00:28:26,455 --> 00:28:27,757
He hates me.

232
00:28:28,616 --> 00:28:29,818
Do you hate him?

233
00:28:31,155 --> 00:28:32,199
No.

234
00:28:34,646 --> 00:28:36,122
Did your mom set that up?

235
00:28:37,206 --> 00:28:38,304
Yes.

236
00:28:41,189 --> 00:28:43,254
Did you ever talk to your mom
about how things are with Tommy?

237
00:28:43,254 --> 00:28:46,386
- I don't tell her things.
- Why not?

238
00:28:46,595 --> 00:28:48,935
She doesn't look at me like everybody else
and I don't want her to.

239
00:28:48,935 --> 00:28:51,174
- I don't want her to know.
- Know what?

240
00:28:52,147 --> 00:28:53,393
That I'm a freak.

241
00:28:54,507 --> 00:28:55,509
Hey.

242
00:28:56,797 --> 00:28:59,837
You are not a freak.
Okay?

243
00:29:00,907 --> 00:29:03,007
Don't you believe anybody that
tries to convince you of that.

244
00:29:03,007 --> 00:29:04,274
That's bullshit!

245
00:29:05,607 --> 00:29:07,760
You don't have to go through
your life believing that.

246
00:29:09,767 --> 00:29:10,776
Okay?

247
00:29:14,098 --> 00:29:15,149
Come on.

248
00:29:19,367 --> 00:29:20,888
You said the "S" word.

249
00:29:20,888 --> 00:29:22,839
Yeah, I know.

250
00:29:23,611 --> 00:29:24,623
Sorry.

251
00:30:33,239 --> 00:30:36,317
So, your Dad lives in Pittsburg
with a lady that works in a tollbooth?

252
00:30:39,593 --> 00:30:41,815
What if she has
to pee when she's working?

253
00:30:42,988 --> 00:30:44,459
Think she just holds it?

254
00:30:45,032 --> 00:30:48,675
I don't know. I was just
thinking about that myself.

255
00:30:49,952 --> 00:30:53,645
You asked a lot of questions
about Dad today. How come?

256
00:30:54,609 --> 00:30:58,565
Well... sometimes we do
things to draw attention,

257
00:30:59,382 --> 00:31:03,313
to express our feelings
about certain issues, uh,

258
00:31:03,722 --> 00:31:05,573
divorce, whatever.

259
00:31:07,102 --> 00:31:09,420
For example, a person might
leave something on a desk

260
00:31:09,420 --> 00:31:11,024
for someone else to find.

261
00:31:15,333 --> 00:31:17,744
Do you know what free-
association writing is, Cole?

262
00:31:19,203 --> 00:31:20,266
No.

263
00:31:21,536 --> 00:31:22,643
Free-association writing

264
00:31:22,643 --> 00:31:25,817
is when you take
a pencil in your hand and...

265
00:31:26,423 --> 00:31:30,081
...you put the pencil
to a piece of paper and you start writing.

266
00:31:31,119 --> 00:31:33,798
And you don't look at what you're writing
or think about what you're writing.

267
00:31:33,798 --> 00:31:36,520
You just...
keep your hand moving.

268
00:31:37,624 --> 00:31:39,264
And after a while,

269
00:31:39,395 --> 00:31:42,374
if you keep your hand moving
long enough, words and thoughts

270
00:31:42,374 --> 00:31:44,986
start coming out that you didn't even
know you had in you.

271
00:31:45,874 --> 00:31:50,674
Could be... something
you heard somewhere else, or...

272
00:31:51,563 --> 00:31:54,062
...feelings you had
deep inside of you.

273
00:31:57,414 --> 00:31:59,898
Have you ever done any
free-association writing, Cole?

274
00:32:03,885 --> 00:32:05,016
Yes.

275
00:32:05,765 --> 00:32:07,034
What did you write?

276
00:32:09,425 --> 00:32:10,876
Upset words.

277
00:32:13,156 --> 00:32:16,085
Did you ever write any upset
words before your father left?

278
00:32:18,349 --> 00:32:19,698
I don't remember.

279
00:32:21,926 --> 00:32:23,424
Can you do
something for me?

280
00:32:26,290 --> 00:32:27,433
I want you to...

281
00:32:27,706 --> 00:32:30,286
...think about what you want
to get out of our time together,

282
00:32:30,818 --> 00:32:32,313
what our goals should be.

283
00:32:33,538 --> 00:32:34,778
Something I want?

284
00:32:37,099 --> 00:32:39,414
If you could change something
in your life, anything at all,

285
00:32:39,545 --> 00:32:40,636
what would it be?

286
00:32:41,817 --> 00:32:43,107
Instead of something I want,

287
00:32:43,107 --> 00:32:44,685
can it be something
I don't want?

288
00:32:47,077 --> 00:32:48,168
Okay.

289
00:32:50,029 --> 00:32:51,870
I don't want
to be scared anymore.

290
00:33:04,958 --> 00:33:06,265
You gonna get that?

291
00:33:13,623 --> 00:33:15,176
Are you gonna get that?

292
00:33:20,238 --> 00:33:22,154
-  Hey.
-  Hi.

293
00:33:22,798 --> 00:33:24,540
Don't you see
enough of me at the store?

294
00:33:24,540 --> 00:33:28,422
I'm on my way out to the flea market
in the Amish country, and I thought...

295
00:33:28,519 --> 00:33:31,198
you'd wanna come along and show me
how to buy at one of these things.

296
00:33:32,309 --> 00:33:35,029
I don't know if I can
deal with the Amish today.

297
00:33:35,199 --> 00:33:38,301
You can't curse or spit
or anything around them.

298
00:33:38,799 --> 00:33:41,331
I just figured maybe
you just wanted to get some air,

299
00:33:41,419 --> 00:33:43,426
because you'd seemed
kind of down lately.

300
00:33:45,550 --> 00:33:48,486
Um... I'm okay.

301
00:33:49,470 --> 00:33:52,120
All right. Do you think that
I should stop by on my way back

302
00:33:52,120 --> 00:33:54,472
and show you what
I got? 'Cause that wouldn't be a problem.

303
00:33:55,600 --> 00:33:58,807
No. I... You know,
I can see 'em on Monday.

304
00:33:59,110 --> 00:34:00,991
Sure. Yeah, that's fine. Understood.

305
00:34:01,978 --> 00:34:03,930
Okay, so I guess
I'm gonna get going then,

306
00:34:03,930 --> 00:34:06,069
- and I'll speak to you later.
- Okay.

307
00:34:06,170 --> 00:34:08,301
- Don't step in horse manure.
- Well, thank you very much.

308
00:34:18,529 --> 00:34:20,440
Keep moving, cheese-dick.

309
00:34:44,952 --> 00:34:47,229
Can anybody guess what city

310
00:34:47,229 --> 00:34:49,566
was capital of
the United States of America

311
00:34:49,566 --> 00:34:54,076
from 1790 to 1800?

312
00:34:57,013 --> 00:35:00,692
I'll give you a hint:
It's the city you live in.

313
00:35:00,692 --> 00:35:03,659
-  Philadelphia.
- Right, right.

314
00:35:03,659 --> 00:35:06,033
Philadelphia's one of the
oldest cities in this country.

315
00:35:06,033 --> 00:35:09,091
A lot of generations have
lived here and died here.

316
00:35:09,183 --> 00:35:10,643
Almost any place
you go in this city

317
00:35:10,643 --> 00:35:13,272
has a history
and a story behind it.

318
00:35:13,633 --> 00:35:16,303
Even this school
and the grounds it sits on.

319
00:35:16,724 --> 00:35:20,020
Can anyone guess what
this building was used for

320
00:35:20,020 --> 00:35:22,584
a hundred years ago,
before you went to school here,

321
00:35:22,715 --> 00:35:24,854
before I went
to this school, even?

322
00:35:32,855 --> 00:35:34,324
Yes. Cole.

323
00:35:36,824 --> 00:35:38,774
They used to hang people here.

324
00:35:43,737 --> 00:35:45,859
No. Uh, that...
Mm-mmm. That's not correct.

325
00:35:45,859 --> 00:35:47,491
Uh, where'd you hear that?

326
00:35:48,298 --> 00:35:49,556
They'd pull the people in,

327
00:35:49,556 --> 00:35:51,750
crying and kissing
their families bye.

328
00:35:52,746 --> 00:35:56,037
People watching...
spit at them.

329
00:35:58,020 --> 00:36:02,103
U-Uh, Cole, this-this building
was a legal courthouse.

330
00:36:02,706 --> 00:36:03,758
Laws were passed here,

331
00:36:03,758 --> 00:36:06,129
some of the very first
laws of this country.

332
00:36:06,129 --> 00:36:09,483
This whole building was
full of lawyers, lawmakers.

333
00:36:09,483 --> 00:36:11,343
They were the ones
that hanged everybody.

334
00:36:13,846 --> 00:36:14,883
Um...

335
00:36:15,900 --> 00:36:18,626
I don't... I don't know which
one of these guys told you that,

336
00:36:18,626 --> 00:36:22,298
but, um... they were
just trying to scare you.

337
00:36:31,867 --> 00:36:34,426
I don't like people
looking at me like that.

338
00:36:36,766 --> 00:36:37,932
Like what?

339
00:36:38,166 --> 00:36:39,370
Stop it!

340
00:36:40,016 --> 00:36:43,506
I, uh... I-I-I don't
know how else to look.

341
00:36:45,386 --> 00:36:47,498
You're Stuttering Stanley!

342
00:36:50,887 --> 00:36:51,968
Excuse me?

343
00:36:52,227 --> 00:36:53,695
You talked funny when you
went to school here.

344
00:36:53,695 --> 00:36:55,959
You talked funny all the way
to high school.

345
00:36:56,127 --> 00:36:57,137
What?

346
00:36:57,137 --> 00:36:59,943
You shouldn't look at people.
It makes them feel bad.

347
00:36:59,943 --> 00:37:02,119
- How did you...
- Stop looking at me!

348
00:37:02,119 --> 00:37:05,604
Who have you...
b-b-been speaking-ing to?

349
00:37:05,604 --> 00:37:08,585
Stuttering Stanley!
Stuttering Stanley!

350
00:37:08,585 --> 00:37:10,287
- Stop it.
- Stuttering Stanley!

351
00:37:10,287 --> 00:37:13,896
- S-S-Stop... Stop that!
- Stuttering Stanley!

352
00:37:13,896 --> 00:37:16,703
- Stuttering Stanley!
- S-S-Stop it.

353
00:37:16,834 --> 00:37:19,188
Stuttering Stanley!
Stuttering Stanley!

354
00:37:19,188 --> 00:37:22,579
Shut up, you f-f-f-freak!

355
00:37:37,329 --> 00:37:38,399
Hey, big guy.

356
00:37:43,859 --> 00:37:45,134
How's it going?

357
00:37:45,459 --> 00:37:47,545
I don't wanna talk
about anything right now.

358
00:37:48,479 --> 00:37:49,503
Okay.

359
00:38:05,080 --> 00:38:06,235
You like magic?

360
00:38:08,600 --> 00:38:09,662
Hmm?

361
00:38:13,380 --> 00:38:16,626
the magic penny.

362
00:38:17,690 --> 00:38:19,338
Looks like
an ordinary penny.

363
00:38:20,391 --> 00:38:22,404
But I do my little
magic shake, and...

364
00:38:24,281 --> 00:38:25,881
...now it's in my right hand.

365
00:38:26,791 --> 00:38:28,706
But that's not the end
of the magic trick.

366
00:38:29,861 --> 00:38:31,920
I do another
little shake, and...

367
00:38:34,991 --> 00:38:36,517
...right there
in the vest pocket.

368
00:38:38,391 --> 00:38:40,209
But that's not the end
of the magic trick.

369
00:38:41,095 --> 00:38:42,797
I do another little shake...

370
00:38:43,492 --> 00:38:44,597
and...

371
00:38:46,882 --> 00:38:49,642
...right back in
the left hand where it started.

372
00:38:52,052 --> 00:38:53,385
That isn't magic.

373
00:38:53,872 --> 00:38:57,248
What are you talking about?
Of course it's magic.

374
00:38:57,552 --> 00:38:59,999
You just kept the penny
in that hand the whole time.

375
00:39:05,322 --> 00:39:06,468
Think so?

376
00:39:08,472 --> 00:39:10,315
I didn't know you were funny.

377
00:39:25,387 --> 00:39:29,279
Malcolm, sit your
cute butt down and listen up.

378
00:39:30,377 --> 00:39:33,929
No doubt about it.
Anna is like my sister.

379
00:39:34,654 --> 00:39:37,881
And you better make her happy.
And I'm not talking about no...

380
00:39:37,881 --> 00:39:40,900
..."Mmm! This taste like
real butter" kind of happy.

381
00:39:40,900 --> 00:39:43,290
I'm talking about...
What's up, girl?

382
00:39:43,421 --> 00:39:46,018
"Julie Andrews,
mm-hmm, twirling around

383
00:39:46,018 --> 00:39:48,859
like a mental patient on
a mountaintop" kind of happy.

384
00:39:48,859 --> 00:39:51,351
Now, that's the kind
of happy I'm talking about.

385
00:39:53,045 --> 00:39:54,121
Shh. Come here.

386
00:39:54,121 --> 00:39:56,199
Shh. Don't tell her I told you,

387
00:39:56,608 --> 00:39:59,993
but she said
she knew she love you...

388
00:39:59,993 --> 00:40:02,963
from the first time
she met you on the street.

389
00:40:04,350 --> 00:40:06,495
She'd do anything for you.

390
00:40:06,975 --> 00:40:10,552
I love you guys.

391
00:40:13,710 --> 00:40:15,834
My nose is running.
Turn it...

392
00:41:34,809 --> 00:41:36,875
And then you do
the magic shake.

393
00:41:37,801 --> 00:41:39,948
The penny has moved
from my pocket...

394
00:41:40,714 --> 00:41:42,893
...all the way back
to the hand it started in.

395
00:41:45,714 --> 00:41:47,097
That's stupid.

396
00:41:49,636 --> 00:41:51,034
It's supposed to be funny.

397
00:41:52,350 --> 00:41:53,686
It's stupid.

398
00:41:54,249 --> 00:41:55,864
I want my penny back.

399
00:41:58,446 --> 00:42:00,552
He doesn't
get invited places, so...

400
00:42:00,552 --> 00:42:01,739
It's our pleasure.

401
00:42:02,010 --> 00:42:05,278
Last time was a Chuck E. Cheese
party a year ago.

402
00:42:05,278 --> 00:42:07,165
He hid in
one of those purple,

403
00:42:07,165 --> 00:42:09,410
plastic tunnels
and didn't come out.

404
00:42:09,513 --> 00:42:13,085
- Chucky who?
- Cheese. It's a kids place.

405
00:42:13,451 --> 00:42:15,830
-  Excuse me.
-  Sorry.

406
00:42:45,165 --> 00:42:46,306
Sir.

407
00:42:48,042 --> 00:42:49,152
Madam?

408
00:42:50,257 --> 00:42:51,602
Is someone
out there?

409
00:42:53,391 --> 00:42:55,872
Open this door, please.
Come on.

410
00:42:55,872 --> 00:42:57,264
I can't breathe.

411
00:42:58,033 --> 00:43:00,005
If you can hear me,
open this door.

412
00:43:01,093 --> 00:43:04,229
I swear on my life I didn't
take the master's horse.

413
00:43:05,060 --> 00:43:08,760
Open this door, or I'll break
through it and grab you!

414
00:43:09,281 --> 00:43:12,300
The star of the commercial
always gets his own trailer.

415
00:43:12,300 --> 00:43:13,455
For what?

416
00:43:13,586 --> 00:43:16,484
He needs a place to think
about his character, alone.

417
00:43:16,653 --> 00:43:18,526
You only had one line.

418
00:43:22,190 --> 00:43:24,276
Darren, check it out.

419
00:43:24,964 --> 00:43:26,035
Oh, yeah.

420
00:43:26,035 --> 00:43:28,195
My dad made me invite him.

421
00:43:46,625 --> 00:43:48,269
Happy birthday, Darren.

422
00:43:50,185 --> 00:43:51,768
Is there something
you wanna see in there?

423
00:43:51,768 --> 00:43:52,851
No.

424
00:43:56,196 --> 00:43:58,328
We're gonna
put on a pretend play.

425
00:43:59,121 --> 00:44:00,368
Wanna be in it?

426
00:44:01,478 --> 00:44:02,517
Okay.

427
00:44:03,549 --> 00:44:05,301
It's called
Locked in the Dungeon.

428
00:44:06,119 --> 00:44:09,775
Yeah, Cole, and... you get to be
the one locked in the dungeon.

429
00:44:13,475 --> 00:44:15,999
Don't! Don't!
Don't! Don't!

430
00:44:16,129 --> 00:44:18,456
No! Don't!

431
00:44:18,456 --> 00:44:23,367
-  No! No! No! No! No! No!
- Let me out!

432
00:44:45,203 --> 00:44:47,573
Help! Help! Help!

433
00:44:47,573 --> 00:44:49,208
- Cole?
- Oh, no!

434
00:44:49,339 --> 00:44:51,906
- Help! Help!

435
00:44:52,037 --> 00:44:54,518
- Cole!

436
00:44:54,648 --> 00:44:57,258
- Oh, my God. Is there a key for this door?
- Help me!

437
00:44:57,258 --> 00:44:59,682
Cole? Honey, honey,
can you hear me?

438
00:44:59,682 --> 00:45:02,395
- Open the door!
- God!

439
00:45:02,526 --> 00:45:05,442
- No!

440
00:45:05,572 --> 00:45:08,445
- Oh, my God, Cole!
- Oh, my God! Help me!

441
00:45:08,575 --> 00:45:10,795
- Help! Help!

442
00:45:22,979 --> 00:45:25,653
The tests would indicate
he did not have a seizure.

443
00:45:26,509 --> 00:45:28,019
He's doing fine.

444
00:45:28,509 --> 00:45:30,617
After some rest,
he can go home tonight.

445
00:45:37,519 --> 00:45:40,957
There's some cuts
and bruises on your son

446
00:45:41,542 --> 00:45:43,718
- that are concerning me.
- Oh, man.

447
00:45:45,962 --> 00:45:47,950
Yeah, those are from sports.

448
00:45:53,927 --> 00:45:55,650
You think I hurt my child?

449
00:45:59,977 --> 00:46:01,338
You think I'm a bad mother?

450
00:46:02,521 --> 00:46:04,242
Mrs. Sloan over there,

451
00:46:04,841 --> 00:46:07,028
she's a social worker
with the hospital,

452
00:46:07,291 --> 00:46:10,379
and she's gonna ask you
a couple procedural questions.

453
00:46:11,336 --> 00:46:14,464
What happened
to my child today?

454
00:46:15,001 --> 00:46:17,309
Something was happening to him,
physically happening.

455
00:46:17,309 --> 00:46:19,432
Something
was very wrong!

456
00:46:23,739 --> 00:46:24,804
Hey.

457
00:46:37,012 --> 00:46:39,264
Did your father used to
tell you bedtime stories?

458
00:46:49,986 --> 00:46:52,790
Once upon a time,
there was this young prince,

459
00:46:54,063 --> 00:46:57,863
and he decided that
he wanted to go for a drive.

460
00:46:57,863 --> 00:47:01,220
And he got
his driver,

461
00:47:01,220 --> 00:47:03,173
and they
started driving.

462
00:47:03,661 --> 00:47:05,119
Driving, driving.

463
00:47:07,265 --> 00:47:10,699
Driving a lot,
and, uh... um...

464
00:47:11,811 --> 00:47:13,933
...they drove so much
that he fell asleep.

465
00:47:15,244 --> 00:47:17,101
And...

466
00:47:20,191 --> 00:47:23,381
Then he woke up, and he realized
they were still driving.

467
00:47:24,424 --> 00:47:26,980
- This was a very long trip.
- Dr. Crowe?

468
00:47:28,286 --> 00:47:30,647
You haven't told
bedtime stories before.

469
00:47:31,045 --> 00:47:33,273
Uh, not too many, no.

470
00:47:33,675 --> 00:47:35,957
Well, you have to add
some twists and stuff.

471
00:47:37,745 --> 00:47:40,038
Okay. Some twists.

472
00:47:42,015 --> 00:47:44,804
Like what kind of twists?
Give me an example.

473
00:47:46,555 --> 00:47:48,638
Maybe they run out of gas.

474
00:47:48,885 --> 00:47:50,145
They run
out of gas?

475
00:47:50,145 --> 00:47:52,066
That's good, 'cause
they're driving, right?

476
00:47:52,956 --> 00:47:55,241
- Okay...
- Tell me the story about why you're sad.

477
00:47:58,710 --> 00:48:00,096
You think I'm sad?

478
00:48:03,584 --> 00:48:05,280
What makes you think that?

479
00:48:07,772 --> 00:48:09,300
Your eyes told me.

480
00:48:11,636 --> 00:48:14,003
I'm not supposed to talk
about stuff like that.

481
00:48:25,564 --> 00:48:28,788
Once upon a time, there was
this person named Malcolm.

482
00:48:29,545 --> 00:48:31,097
He worked with children.

483
00:48:32,847 --> 00:48:33,995
He loved it.

484
00:48:35,574 --> 00:48:37,904
He loved it more
than anything else.

485
00:48:41,028 --> 00:48:44,028
And then one night,
he found out that he made a...

486
00:48:44,476 --> 00:48:46,105
...mistake with one of them.

487
00:48:47,013 --> 00:48:48,439
He couldn't
help that one.

488
00:48:50,538 --> 00:48:55,159
And he can't stop thinking
about it. He... can't forget.

489
00:48:58,554 --> 00:49:00,624
Ever since then,
things have been different.

490
00:49:02,646 --> 00:49:05,355
He's not the same person
that he used to be.

491
00:49:07,932 --> 00:49:12,289
And his wife... doesn't like
the person that he's become.

492
00:49:13,724 --> 00:49:16,344
They barely speak anymore.
They're like strangers.

493
00:49:19,779 --> 00:49:22,921
And then one day, Malcolm
meets this wonderful little boy.

494
00:49:23,406 --> 00:49:26,192
A really cool
little boy.

495
00:49:27,498 --> 00:49:29,516
Reminds him a lot
of the other one.

496
00:49:32,372 --> 00:49:35,284
And Malcolm decides
to try and help this new boy...

497
00:49:37,639 --> 00:49:41,500
...'cause he feels that
if he can help this new boy,

498
00:49:42,513 --> 00:49:46,516
be like...
helping that other one too.

499
00:49:49,991 --> 00:49:51,954
How does the story end?

500
00:49:54,134 --> 00:49:55,268
I don't know.

501
00:50:13,892 --> 00:50:16,046
I want to tell you
my secret now.

502
00:50:21,133 --> 00:50:22,146
Okay.

503
00:50:30,112 --> 00:50:32,068
I see dead people.

504
00:50:35,482 --> 00:50:37,128
In your dreams?

505
00:50:40,027 --> 00:50:41,404
While you're awake?

506
00:50:47,494 --> 00:50:50,742
Dead people, like,
in graves and coffins?

507
00:50:51,904 --> 00:50:54,342
Walking around
like regular people.

508
00:50:55,383 --> 00:50:56,894
They don't
see each other.

509
00:50:57,758 --> 00:51:00,197
They only see
what they want to see.

510
00:51:01,884 --> 00:51:03,604
They don't know they're dead.

511
00:51:06,427 --> 00:51:08,003
How often do you see them?

512
00:51:12,064 --> 00:51:13,694
All the time.

513
00:51:16,916 --> 00:51:18,523
They're
everywhere.

514
00:51:21,878 --> 00:51:24,505
You won't tell anyone
my secret, right?

515
00:51:25,155 --> 00:51:27,600
No. I promise.

516
00:51:29,885 --> 00:51:32,076
Will you stay here
until I fall asleep?

517
00:51:34,635 --> 00:51:35,867
Of course.

518
00:51:47,236 --> 00:51:52,523
Cole... has pathologies more
severe than initially assessed.

519
00:51:53,868 --> 00:51:56,329
He's suffering from
visual hallucinations,

520
00:51:56,840 --> 00:51:59,299
- paranoia...

521
00:51:59,728 --> 00:52:03,791
...some kind of...
school-age schizophrenia.

522
00:52:05,750 --> 00:52:09,316
Medication, hospitalization
may be required.

523
00:52:14,716 --> 00:52:17,291
And I'm not helping him.

524
00:53:45,251 --> 00:53:47,443
Hi. This is Lynn Sear,
Cole's mom.

525
00:53:49,466 --> 00:53:53,581
Yeah. Uh, yeah, I-I'd like
to talk to you about your boy

526
00:53:53,581 --> 00:53:56,909
and his friends keeping
their goddamn hands off my son.

527
00:55:34,837 --> 00:55:35,891
Mama?

528
00:55:37,181 --> 00:55:38,249
No.

529
00:55:38,716 --> 00:55:40,920
Dinner is not ready!

530
00:55:41,453 --> 00:55:42,810
What are
you gonna do?

531
00:55:43,306 --> 00:55:45,769
Y-You can't hurt me anymore!

532
00:55:47,056 --> 00:55:50,329
Neddy, you're
a terrible husband, Neddy!

533
00:55:50,329 --> 00:55:53,901
Look what you
made me do! Neddy!

534
00:56:04,017 --> 00:56:07,828
I'm okay. Okay. Okay.

535
00:56:12,967 --> 00:56:14,857
Once there was a boy,

536
00:56:15,257 --> 00:56:18,013
very different from
all the other boys.

537
00:56:18,838 --> 00:56:20,973
He lived in the jungle...

538
00:56:21,908 --> 00:56:24,815
...and he could speak
to the animals.

539
00:56:39,818 --> 00:56:42,295
Did you think
the play sucked big time?

540
00:56:42,691 --> 00:56:44,667
Heh. What?

541
00:56:45,509 --> 00:56:48,653
Tommy Tammisimo acted
in a cough syrup commercial.

542
00:56:48,784 --> 00:56:51,768
He said everyone was
self-conscious and unrealistic.

543
00:56:51,768 --> 00:56:54,137
He said the play
sucked big time.

544
00:56:54,268 --> 00:56:56,669
This Tommy kid
sounds like a real punk.

545
00:56:58,659 --> 00:57:01,806
I thought the play was
excellent. Better than Cats.

546
00:57:02,670 --> 00:57:04,978
- Cats?
- Never mind.

547
00:57:07,666 --> 00:57:08,800
Cole, I was really interested

548
00:57:08,800 --> 00:57:10,626
in what you told me
at the hospital.

549
00:57:11,520 --> 00:57:13,079
I'd like to hear
more about it.

550
00:57:23,680 --> 00:57:24,748
Cole?

551
00:57:29,181 --> 00:57:30,248
What?

552
00:57:43,271 --> 00:57:44,659
Something up there?

553
00:57:50,283 --> 00:57:51,321
Cole?

554
00:57:55,412 --> 00:57:56,990
I don't see anything.

555
00:58:02,012 --> 00:58:03,528
Be real still.

556
00:58:08,482 --> 00:58:10,805
Sometimes you feel it inside,

557
00:58:10,963 --> 00:58:13,258
like you're falling
down real fast,

558
00:58:13,783 --> 00:58:16,145
but you're really
just standing still.

559
00:58:21,523 --> 00:58:24,747
Do you ever feel the prickly
things on the back of your neck?

560
00:58:25,593 --> 00:58:26,740
Yes.

561
00:58:28,703 --> 00:58:32,181
And the tiny hairs on your arm,
you know, when they stand up?

562
00:58:32,633 --> 00:58:33,763
Yes.

563
00:58:36,854 --> 00:58:38,133
That's them.

564
00:58:42,294 --> 00:58:43,675
When they get mad...

565
00:58:48,424 --> 00:58:49,772
...it gets cold.

566
00:59:07,609 --> 00:59:11,130
I don't see anything.
Are you sure they're there?

567
00:59:12,985 --> 00:59:14,043
Cole?

568
00:59:17,053 --> 00:59:18,820
Please make them leave.

569
00:59:20,057 --> 00:59:21,485
I'm workin' on it.

570
00:59:24,496 --> 00:59:25,637
Come on.

571
00:59:53,787 --> 00:59:56,790
Aah!

572
01:00:11,632 --> 01:00:13,939
Mommy, Daddy?

573
01:00:17,108 --> 01:00:19,423
My throat hurts.

574
01:00:27,822 --> 01:00:28,959
Run! Run!

575
01:00:31,653 --> 01:00:33,668
Pedia Ease cough suppressant.

576
01:00:33,668 --> 01:00:36,292
Gentle, fast, eff...

577
01:00:36,639 --> 01:00:37,797
Cole.

578
01:00:38,939 --> 01:00:42,012
Oh, I don't care what they say.
This thing is broken.

579
01:00:49,976 --> 01:00:51,154
Take 'em off.

580
01:00:55,939 --> 01:00:57,549
I don't want them
on my table.

581
01:01:03,019 --> 01:01:05,611
I saw what was in your bureau
drawer when I was cleaning.

582
01:01:06,080 --> 01:01:07,717
Got something
you want to confess?

583
01:01:11,129 --> 01:01:12,233
Hmm?

584
01:01:12,913 --> 01:01:16,208
The bumblebee pendant?
Why do you keep taking it?

585
01:01:21,096 --> 01:01:22,593
It was Grandma's.

586
01:01:23,470 --> 01:01:26,308
You know, what if it broke?
You know how sad I'd be.

587
01:01:28,930 --> 01:01:31,601
You'd cry 'cause you
miss Grandma so much.

588
01:01:32,890 --> 01:01:34,046
That's right.

589
01:01:39,214 --> 01:01:42,771
Sometimes people think
they lose things...

590
01:01:44,686 --> 01:01:47,613
...and they really didn't
lose them, it just gets moved.

591
01:01:48,603 --> 01:01:50,399
So, did you move
the bumblebee pendant?

592
01:01:59,411 --> 01:02:00,625
Don't get mad.

593
01:02:01,531 --> 01:02:02,922
So, who moved
it this time?

594
01:02:03,362 --> 01:02:06,344
Maybe someone came in our house,
took the bumblebee pendant

595
01:02:06,344 --> 01:02:09,169
out of my closet and placed
it nicely in your drawer.

596
01:02:10,800 --> 01:02:14,187
- Maybe.
- God, I am so tired, Cole.

597
01:02:14,187 --> 01:02:16,862
I'm tired in my body,
I'm tired in my mind,

598
01:02:16,862 --> 01:02:19,205
I'm... tired in my heart.

599
01:02:19,888 --> 01:02:22,995
I need some help. You know,
I don't know if you noticed,

600
01:02:22,995 --> 01:02:25,143
but our little family
isn't doing so good.

601
01:02:26,423 --> 01:02:30,119
I mean, I've been praying,
but I must not be praying right.

602
01:02:31,635 --> 01:02:34,483
Looks like we're just gonna have
to answer each other's prayers.

603
01:02:38,133 --> 01:02:40,462
If we can't talk to each other,
we're not gonna make it.

604
01:02:44,748 --> 01:02:48,149
Now, tell me, baby.
I-I... I won't get mad, honey.

605
01:02:48,494 --> 01:02:50,786
Did you take
the bumblebee pendant?

606
01:02:59,554 --> 01:03:00,812
- No.

607
01:03:03,768 --> 01:03:06,648
You've had enough roast beef.
You need to leave the table.

608
01:03:09,095 --> 01:03:10,260
Go!

609
01:03:34,334 --> 01:03:35,523
Hey, come on.

610
01:03:35,866 --> 01:03:38,491
I'll show you where
my dad keeps his gun. Come on.

611
01:03:44,463 --> 01:03:47,215
Sebastian, come on.

612
01:03:47,988 --> 01:03:49,050
Mama?

613
01:03:56,614 --> 01:03:58,255
If you're not very mad,

614
01:03:59,337 --> 01:04:01,315
can I sleep
in your bed tonight?

615
01:04:03,787 --> 01:04:05,179
Look at my face.

616
01:04:06,422 --> 01:04:08,314
I'm not very mad.

617
01:04:13,667 --> 01:04:15,876
Baby, why are you shaking?

618
01:04:17,148 --> 01:04:18,867
Cole, what's wrong?

619
01:04:19,673 --> 01:04:23,155
Oh, God,
please tell me!

620
01:04:23,428 --> 01:04:25,245
Oh, please.

621
01:04:28,900 --> 01:04:30,254
Oh.

622
01:04:39,819 --> 01:04:41,347
It's Edwardian,

623
01:04:41,697 --> 01:04:44,326
beautifully worked
with mine-cut diamonds

624
01:04:44,326 --> 01:04:47,183
and an actual color
Burmese sapphire.

625
01:04:48,019 --> 01:04:49,850
It's timeless.

626
01:04:50,622 --> 01:04:51,789
Oh.

627
01:04:53,521 --> 01:04:55,580
You, uh...

628
01:04:55,711 --> 01:04:57,450
...got anything
a little plainer?

629
01:04:58,489 --> 01:04:59,758
Plainer?

630
01:04:59,889 --> 01:05:03,369
You want a plain ring to go with your
plain fiancÃ©? Is that how it is?

631
01:05:03,369 --> 01:05:06,636
No! Baby, don't...
don't get in a tizzy.

632
01:05:09,490 --> 01:05:10,558
Uh...

633
01:05:11,410 --> 01:05:12,938
You're so beautiful.

634
01:05:14,190 --> 01:05:17,734
Y-You're like a Burmese
sapphire all by yourself.

635
01:05:17,864 --> 01:05:20,090
- You don't need all that.
- Uh-huh.

636
01:05:20,954 --> 01:05:25,350
Why don't you try it on and see
how you both feel about it?

637
01:05:30,922 --> 01:05:33,141
There.
How does that feel?

638
01:05:34,661 --> 01:05:38,561
I think this piece, um,
communicates a longing.

639
01:05:38,981 --> 01:05:41,533
I imagine that
the woman who owned it

640
01:05:41,976 --> 01:05:44,616
loved a man that
she couldn't be with.

641
01:05:46,581 --> 01:05:49,724
Did he have wavy hair
and chestnut eyes?

642
01:05:49,812 --> 01:05:53,859
- What?
- Um, I-I don't know, but...

643
01:05:53,989 --> 01:05:56,532
...a lot of the pieces
in this store communicate,

644
01:05:56,532 --> 01:05:59,996
and I think you should choose
a piece that speaks to you.

645
01:06:01,919 --> 01:06:05,958
I think maybe when people own
things and then they pass away,

646
01:06:06,812 --> 01:06:10,136
a part of themselves gets
printed on those things,

647
01:06:10,266 --> 01:06:13,793
like...
like fingerprints.

648
01:06:16,128 --> 01:06:17,405
I'll just wrap it up.

649
01:06:25,256 --> 01:06:27,154
You don't need a guy
with a master's.

650
01:06:27,569 --> 01:06:30,287
You need a wrestler with
a neck larger than his head.

651
01:06:30,287 --> 01:06:33,334
No, I need
a wrestler with a master's.

652
01:06:34,596 --> 01:06:36,871
- What's this?
- Happy birthday.

653
01:06:37,377 --> 01:06:38,963
- From you?
- Mm-hmm.

654
01:06:46,957 --> 01:06:48,151
It's a...

655
01:06:49,614 --> 01:06:50,921
...first edition.

656
01:06:51,524 --> 01:06:52,781
- Wow.

657
01:06:53,959 --> 01:06:55,418
Oh, this is too much.

658
01:06:55,418 --> 01:06:58,970
No. Took it out of
your Christmas bonus.

659
01:07:00,535 --> 01:07:02,303
It's perfect, Anna.

660
01:07:03,397 --> 01:07:04,472
Thanks.

661
01:07:11,342 --> 01:07:13,181
What do you want
more than anything?

662
01:07:14,269 --> 01:07:15,514
I don't know.

663
01:07:16,513 --> 01:07:18,074
I told you what I want.

664
01:07:22,038 --> 01:07:23,495
I know what I want.

665
01:07:26,166 --> 01:07:28,482
I want to be able
to talk to my wife again...

666
01:07:31,276 --> 01:07:33,179
...the way we used
to talk to each other...

667
01:07:34,746 --> 01:07:37,401
...like there was no one
else in the world except us.

668
01:07:39,586 --> 01:07:41,309
How are you gonna do that?

669
01:07:46,837 --> 01:07:48,806
I can't be
your doctor anymore.

670
01:07:50,257 --> 01:07:52,840
I haven't paid enough
attention to my family.

671
01:07:53,714 --> 01:07:55,666
Bad things happen
when you do that.

672
01:07:57,497 --> 01:07:58,790
Do you understand?

673
01:08:00,547 --> 01:08:02,471
I'm going to transfer you.
I know two psychol...

674
01:08:02,601 --> 01:08:04,077
Don't fail me.

675
01:08:06,498 --> 01:08:09,241
Don't give up. You're the only
one who can help me. I know it.

676
01:08:10,698 --> 01:08:12,062
I can't help you.

677
01:08:15,267 --> 01:08:16,358
You...

678
01:08:17,661 --> 01:08:19,351
Someone else can help you.

679
01:08:23,101 --> 01:08:25,084
You believe me, right?

680
01:08:30,029 --> 01:08:32,503
Dr. Crowe,
you believe my secret, right?

681
01:08:34,835 --> 01:08:36,649
I don't know how
to answer that, Cole.

682
01:08:47,902 --> 01:08:49,589
How can you help me...

683
01:08:50,859 --> 01:08:53,028
...if you don't believe me?

684
01:08:57,910 --> 01:08:59,963
Some magic's real.

685
01:09:16,595 --> 01:09:19,325
Do you know why
you're afraid when you're alone?

686
01:09:22,033 --> 01:09:24,352
I do. I do.

687
01:09:31,675 --> 01:09:32,846
I'm sorry about that, Vincent.

688
01:09:32,846 --> 01:09:34,866
I hope I didn't
leave you alone too long.

689
01:09:35,951 --> 01:09:40,521
- Whew. It's cold in here.

690
01:09:41,802 --> 01:09:44,665
Vincent, why are you crying?

691
01:09:49,427 --> 01:09:53,108
You won't believe.

692
01:09:57,612 --> 01:09:59,221
- I'm sorry about that, Vincent.

693
01:09:59,221 --> 01:10:01,209
I hope I didn't
leave you alone too long.

694
01:10:02,292 --> 01:10:06,112
- Whew. It's cold in here.

695
01:10:08,219 --> 01:10:10,343
- Vincent...

696
01:10:10,474 --> 01:10:13,898
- Whew. It's cold in here.

697
01:10:21,873 --> 01:10:24,358
No, you know what?
I never liked 'em either.

698
01:10:24,674 --> 01:10:27,013
When I was a kid,
I had this blood test done,

699
01:10:27,144 --> 01:10:30,685
and I threw up chili cheese
fries all over this male nurse.

700
01:10:32,976 --> 01:10:35,413
Excuse me.
Dr. Reed is on line two.

701
01:10:35,849 --> 01:10:38,459
Vincent, will you excuse me?
I have to take this.

702
01:10:38,574 --> 01:10:40,723
- Just give me a minute, okay?
- Okay.

703
01:11:54,364 --> 01:11:55,618
No entiendes.

704
01:11:56,478 --> 01:11:57,774
No entiendes.

705
01:11:58,326 --> 01:12:00,998
Yo no quiero morir.

706
01:12:00,998 --> 01:12:04,288
Yo no quiero morir...

707
01:12:08,336 --> 01:12:09,729
Yo no quiero morir.

708
01:12:09,859 --> 01:12:13,297
- Oh, my God.
- Yo no quiero morir!

709
01:12:19,429 --> 01:12:20,918
You been
running around?

710
01:12:25,119 --> 01:12:26,488
Make you feel better?

711
01:12:28,855 --> 01:12:31,447
I like to run around.
It's good exercise.

712
01:12:35,289 --> 01:12:37,074
Do you wanna
ask me questions now?

713
01:12:39,910 --> 01:12:43,365
Wanna be a lance corporal in Company M,
Third Battalion, Seventh Marines?

714
01:12:43,365 --> 01:12:45,659
We're being dispatched
into the Quang Nam province.

715
01:12:46,390 --> 01:12:47,525
Maybe later.

716
01:12:50,890 --> 01:12:52,558
Something happened,
didn't it?

717
01:12:56,185 --> 01:12:57,430
You wiggin' out?

718
01:13:00,362 --> 01:13:01,391
Yes.

719
01:13:02,430 --> 01:13:03,588
I think I am.

720
01:13:06,103 --> 01:13:09,157
Do you know what
"yo no quiero morir" means?

721
01:13:09,621 --> 01:13:12,942
It's Spanish. It means
"I don't want to die."

722
01:13:15,471 --> 01:13:17,898
What do you think these ghosts
want when they talk to you?

723
01:13:26,260 --> 01:13:27,978
I want you
to think about it, Cole.

724
01:13:29,892 --> 01:13:32,084
I want you to think
about it really carefully.

725
01:13:33,512 --> 01:13:34,964
What do you think they want?

726
01:13:39,855 --> 01:13:41,128
Just help.

727
01:13:41,259 --> 01:13:43,827
That's right.
That's what I think too.

728
01:13:44,490 --> 01:13:46,699
They just want help,
even the scary ones.

729
01:13:47,494 --> 01:13:49,789
And I think I might know
a way to make them go away.

730
01:13:50,253 --> 01:13:51,296
How?

731
01:13:53,174 --> 01:13:54,277
Listen to them.

732
01:13:56,973 --> 01:13:58,443
What if they
don't want help?

733
01:13:59,282 --> 01:14:01,825
What if they're just angry and
they just want to hurt somebody?

734
01:14:02,912 --> 01:14:04,876
I don't think
that's the way it works.

735
01:14:05,153 --> 01:14:06,613
How do you
know for sure?

736
01:14:09,054 --> 01:14:10,316
I don't.

737
01:14:31,859 --> 01:14:32,972
Hey.

738
01:14:34,777 --> 01:14:36,621
Hey! Hey!

739
01:14:56,467 --> 01:14:57,765
What's happening?

740
01:14:59,689 --> 01:15:01,909
What's...
What's happening?

741
01:15:03,716 --> 01:15:04,989
Cole!

742
01:15:09,316 --> 01:15:10,422
What's...

743
01:15:18,861 --> 01:15:20,263
What's happening to you?

744
01:15:21,450 --> 01:15:24,541
Is someone hurting you?
I'll... I will kick their ass.

745
01:15:24,897 --> 01:15:26,717
Cole, if they're
hurting you...

746
01:15:40,383 --> 01:15:42,472
Mama, you sleep now.

747
01:16:36,094 --> 01:16:37,704
Aah!

748
01:17:50,383 --> 01:17:52,408
I'm feeling much better now.

749
01:17:57,253 --> 01:18:00,073
D-Do you want
to tell me something?

750
01:18:36,225 --> 01:18:39,004
She came a long way
to visit me, didn't she?

751
01:18:40,808 --> 01:18:42,020
I guess she did.

752
01:19:29,487 --> 01:19:30,691
Can you get some water?

753
01:19:35,448 --> 01:19:36,772
That's her sister.

754
01:19:55,166 --> 01:19:58,812
...you know, and I went through
this with my father's cancer, but...

755
01:19:59,633 --> 01:20:03,077
I just can't imagine a child
being in bed for two years.

756
01:20:03,077 --> 01:20:05,514
How many...
How many doctors?

757
01:20:05,514 --> 01:20:08,537
- I think it was six.
- Six different doctors?

758
01:20:08,537 --> 01:20:10,969
- I think so, yes.
- Oh.

759
01:20:16,839 --> 01:20:20,850
I just heard the, uh... the
little one is falling ill now.

760
01:20:21,559 --> 01:20:22,701
God help them.

761
01:20:43,281 --> 01:20:44,917
Don't go home, okay?

762
01:20:45,917 --> 01:20:47,371
I definitely won't.

763
01:21:43,196 --> 01:21:44,240
Aah!

764
01:22:46,756 --> 01:22:47,820
Mister?

765
01:22:52,236 --> 01:22:53,572
Excuse me, mister.

766
01:22:58,768 --> 01:23:00,633
Are you Kyra's daddy?

767
01:23:14,785 --> 01:23:16,029
It's for you.

768
01:23:18,572 --> 01:23:20,992
Sh-She wanted
to tell you something.

769
01:23:59,651 --> 01:24:02,487
Oh, no! Here he comes!
Look, he's coming my way. Psst.

770
01:24:06,807 --> 01:24:08,538
Would you like to dance?

771
01:24:09,700 --> 01:24:13,279
Um, well, actually,
I just came with my friends.

772
01:24:13,717 --> 01:24:16,328
Oh. Well, how about this?

773
01:24:16,328 --> 01:24:17,718
We can dance for a little bit,

774
01:24:17,718 --> 01:24:20,137
and if you don't
like the way I dance,

775
01:24:20,470 --> 01:24:22,204
y-you can kick me.

776
01:24:23,010 --> 01:24:24,293
Oh. Okay then.

777
01:25:33,842 --> 01:25:35,976
It's time for lunch, Kyra.

778
01:25:41,504 --> 01:25:44,681
- I'm feeling much better now.
- That's so great, honey.

779
01:25:45,103 --> 01:25:46,814
It's time for your food.

780
01:25:48,555 --> 01:25:50,513
Can I go outside
if I eat this?

781
01:25:50,644 --> 01:25:53,473
I don't know. You know how
you get sick in the afternoons.

782
01:25:53,603 --> 01:25:54,760
We'll see.

783
01:25:57,806 --> 01:25:59,115
Don't say that
it tastes funny.

784
01:25:59,115 --> 01:26:00,931
You know I don't
like to hear that.

785
01:26:04,368 --> 01:26:06,008
Sammie's
mom called.

786
01:26:23,994 --> 01:26:25,738
You were keeping her sick.

787
01:26:44,245 --> 01:26:45,918
You liked it, she said.

788
01:26:48,962 --> 01:26:50,439
She looked
out for you.

789
01:26:52,266 --> 01:26:54,250
Is Kyra coming back?

790
01:26:57,583 --> 01:26:58,844
Not anymore.

791
01:27:07,586 --> 01:27:09,053
-  All right.
-  I think that's enough.

792
01:27:09,053 --> 01:27:10,729
- That's enough makeup.
- Okay.

793
01:27:12,556 --> 01:27:14,709
They're calling
for the stable boy.

794
01:27:14,709 --> 01:27:16,264
Oh, we have to hurry!

795
01:27:19,457 --> 01:27:22,184
Who, uh...
Who were you talking to?

796
01:27:28,876 --> 01:27:30,965
Just practicing my lines.

797
01:27:35,224 --> 01:27:37,669
Thanks for giving me
this part, Mr. Cunningham.

798
01:27:37,958 --> 01:27:41,707
You know, when I went to school here,
there was a terrible fire in the theater.

799
01:27:41,707 --> 01:27:43,252
They rebuilt the whole thing.

800
01:27:43,849 --> 01:27:45,254
Yeah, I know.

801
01:27:47,113 --> 01:27:49,681
Aw.

802
01:27:57,056 --> 01:27:59,117
Only he who is
pure of heart

803
01:27:59,117 --> 01:28:01,083
can take the sword
from the stone.

804
01:28:01,998 --> 01:28:03,717
Let the boy try.

805
01:28:11,859 --> 01:28:14,937
But he is a stable boy.
He cleans up after the horses.

806
01:28:14,937 --> 01:28:16,796
Silence, village idiot.

807
01:28:18,279 --> 01:28:20,670
Let the boy
step forward.

808
01:28:47,829 --> 01:28:50,701
Hail King Arthur!

809
01:28:56,098 --> 01:28:58,448
Yea!

810
01:28:58,579 --> 01:29:00,711
- Hoorah!

811
01:29:23,472 --> 01:29:25,781
I thought you were really
great in the play, Cole.

812
01:29:25,781 --> 01:29:27,441
- Really?
- Yeah.

813
01:29:28,453 --> 01:29:30,561
- You know what else?
- What?

814
01:29:31,048 --> 01:29:33,611
I thought Tommy Tammisimo
sucked big time.

815
01:29:35,270 --> 01:29:36,388
Ha-ha-ha.

816
01:29:42,442 --> 01:29:45,021
I got an idea how you
can talk to your wife.

817
01:29:46,597 --> 01:29:48,151
Wait till she's asleep.

818
01:29:49,109 --> 01:29:52,295
Then she'll listen to you
and she won't even know it.

819
01:29:59,947 --> 01:30:01,927
I'm not gonna
see you anymore, am I?

820
01:30:05,083 --> 01:30:07,663
I think we said
everything we needed to say.

821
01:30:09,644 --> 01:30:12,482
Maybe it's time to say things
to someone closer to you.

822
01:30:14,624 --> 01:30:17,672
Maybe we can pretend like we're
gonna see each other tomorrow.

823
01:30:20,065 --> 01:30:21,556
Just for pretend.

824
01:30:28,325 --> 01:30:29,512
Okay.

825
01:30:35,205 --> 01:30:36,486
I'm gonna go now.

826
01:30:43,776 --> 01:30:45,496
I'll see you tomorrow, Cole.

827
01:31:13,284 --> 01:31:16,636
I-I'm okay, officer.
I-I'm okay.

828
01:31:16,766 --> 01:31:18,812
I don't know
what happened.

829
01:31:24,608 --> 01:31:25,690
Hmm.

830
01:31:27,678 --> 01:31:30,259
Jeez, I hope
nobody got hurt.

831
01:31:33,958 --> 01:31:35,519
You're very quiet.

832
01:31:37,133 --> 01:31:39,032
You're mad I missed
the play, aren't you?

833
01:31:40,618 --> 01:31:42,545
I have two jobs, baby.

834
01:31:43,011 --> 01:31:45,183
You know how important
they are for us.

835
01:31:48,017 --> 01:31:50,034
I'd give anything
to have been there.

836
01:32:02,466 --> 01:32:04,789
I'm ready
to communicate with you now.

837
01:32:09,953 --> 01:32:11,086
Communicate?

838
01:32:13,696 --> 01:32:15,388
Tell you my secrets.

839
01:32:17,610 --> 01:32:18,704
What is it?

840
01:32:23,880 --> 01:32:25,723
You know
the accident up there?

841
01:32:26,709 --> 01:32:27,792
Yeah?

842
01:32:29,799 --> 01:32:31,172
Someone got hurt.

843
01:32:31,931 --> 01:32:33,100
They did?

844
01:32:34,108 --> 01:32:35,265
A lady.

845
01:32:37,808 --> 01:32:39,019
She died.

846
01:32:40,158 --> 01:32:42,241
Oh, my God.
What, you can see her?

847
01:32:44,021 --> 01:32:45,085
Yes.

848
01:32:45,751 --> 01:32:47,010
Where is she?

849
01:32:50,581 --> 01:32:52,695
Standing
next to my window.

850
01:33:00,672 --> 01:33:02,311
Cole, you're scaring me.

851
01:33:03,835 --> 01:33:05,915
They scare me too sometimes.

852
01:33:08,742 --> 01:33:09,762
They?

853
01:33:14,019 --> 01:33:15,269
Ghosts.

854
01:33:20,141 --> 01:33:21,854
You see ghosts, Cole?

855
01:33:24,857 --> 01:33:26,856
They want me
to do things for them.

856
01:33:30,297 --> 01:33:32,560
They...
They talk to you?

857
01:33:33,653 --> 01:33:34,976
They tell you
to do things?

858
01:33:36,849 --> 01:33:38,937
They're the ones
that used to hurt me.

859
01:33:41,265 --> 01:33:42,914
What are you
thinking, Mama?

860
01:33:44,924 --> 01:33:46,314
You think I'm a freak?

861
01:33:47,044 --> 01:33:48,302
Look at my face.

862
01:33:48,925 --> 01:33:52,015
I would never think
that about you. Ever.

863
01:33:53,190 --> 01:33:55,758
- Got it?
- Got it.

864
01:34:02,896 --> 01:34:04,392
Just let me think
for a minute.

865
01:34:08,946 --> 01:34:10,479
Grandma says hi.

866
01:34:14,343 --> 01:34:17,694
She says she's sorry for
taking the bumblebee pendant.

867
01:34:17,694 --> 01:34:19,398
She just
likes it a lot.

868
01:34:22,728 --> 01:34:23,870
What?

869
01:34:24,435 --> 01:34:26,834
Grandma comes
to visit me sometimes.

870
01:34:29,011 --> 01:34:31,166
Cole, that's very wrong.

871
01:34:31,931 --> 01:34:34,494
- Grandma's gone, you know that.
- I know.

872
01:34:34,986 --> 01:34:36,696
- She wanted me to tell you...
- Cole, please stop.

873
01:34:36,696 --> 01:34:39,476
She wanted me to tell you
she saw you dance.

874
01:34:42,241 --> 01:34:45,717
She said...
when you were little,

875
01:34:46,028 --> 01:34:47,783
you and her
had a fight

876
01:34:48,594 --> 01:34:50,990
right before
your dance recital.

877
01:34:54,637 --> 01:34:57,815
You thought she didn't
come to see you dance.

878
01:35:02,037 --> 01:35:03,358
She did.

879
01:35:09,269 --> 01:35:11,923
She hid in the back
so you wouldn't see.

880
01:35:13,231 --> 01:35:15,809
She said you
were like an angel.

881
01:35:20,938 --> 01:35:22,217
She said...

882
01:35:22,818 --> 01:35:25,732
...you came to the place
where they buried her...

883
01:35:28,588 --> 01:35:30,288
...asked her a question.

884
01:35:33,425 --> 01:35:36,081
She said the answer is...

885
01:35:38,129 --> 01:35:39,499
..."Every day."

886
01:35:42,539 --> 01:35:44,456
What did
you ask?

887
01:35:53,054 --> 01:35:54,151
Do...

888
01:35:56,275 --> 01:35:59,105
Do I make her proud?

889
01:36:03,270 --> 01:36:04,442
Mama.

890
01:36:34,287 --> 01:36:35,572
Hi, everybody.

891
01:36:35,931 --> 01:36:39,363
As most of you know,
I'm not used to doing this,

892
01:36:39,494 --> 01:36:43,367
and, uh, I promised Anna that
I'd try not to embarrass her.

893
01:36:43,731 --> 01:36:45,122
I'll leave that
to her mother.

894
01:36:47,416 --> 01:36:49,853
But we do want to thank
all of you for coming

895
01:36:49,853 --> 01:36:52,551
and for sharing this
wonderful day with us.

896
01:36:52,682 --> 01:36:55,219
It's, uh... bittersweet,
almost, for me,

897
01:36:55,219 --> 01:36:56,998
because I hate
giving her up...

898
01:36:57,892 --> 01:36:59,076
Anna?

899
01:37:10,092 --> 01:37:12,050
I miss you.

900
01:37:17,577 --> 01:37:19,316
I miss you too.

901
01:37:21,206 --> 01:37:23,366
Why, Malcolm?

902
01:37:24,323 --> 01:37:25,357
What?

903
01:37:28,066 --> 01:37:30,907
- What is it? What?
- Why did you leave me?

904
01:37:32,576 --> 01:37:34,158
I didn't leave you.

905
01:37:55,570 --> 01:37:57,225
I see people.

906
01:37:59,829 --> 01:38:01,660
They don't know they're dead.

907
01:38:06,006 --> 01:38:07,684
How often do you see them?

908
01:38:09,490 --> 01:38:10,937
All the time.

909
01:38:14,165 --> 01:38:15,623
They're everywhere.

910
01:38:26,176 --> 01:38:28,560
They only see
what they want to see.

911
01:38:34,472 --> 01:38:35,818
Okay, Mikey.

912
01:38:38,357 --> 01:38:40,961
Come on.
Give me a minute.

913
01:39:19,448 --> 01:39:22,525
- Oh, God. Oh, God, honey.

914
01:39:22,640 --> 01:39:24,057
- Did Vincent...
- Let me see.

915
01:39:24,187 --> 01:39:25,798
It doesn't even hurt.

916
01:39:28,169 --> 01:39:31,484
- Let me see. Take your hand...

917
01:39:31,484 --> 01:39:32,762
Oh, God.

918
01:39:39,247 --> 01:39:41,249
Okay. Okay.

919
01:39:59,600 --> 01:40:03,593
Anna, I think I'm okay.
Really, I think it just went...

920
01:40:04,099 --> 01:40:06,161
...went in and out. I...

921
01:40:09,365 --> 01:40:11,716
It doesn't
even hurt anymore.

922
01:40:42,002 --> 01:40:43,801
I think I can go now.

923
01:40:48,232 --> 01:40:50,756
Just needed
to do a couple things.

924
01:40:55,752 --> 01:40:57,531
I needed
to help someone.

925
01:41:00,680 --> 01:41:02,341
I think I did.

926
01:41:09,210 --> 01:41:11,477
And I needed
to tell you something.

927
01:41:16,923 --> 01:41:18,565
You were never second.

928
01:41:20,194 --> 01:41:21,377
Ever.

929
01:41:24,933 --> 01:41:26,144
I love you.

930
01:41:33,134 --> 01:41:34,731
You sleep now.

931
01:41:37,239 --> 01:41:39,448
Everything will be
different in the morning.

932
01:41:45,814 --> 01:41:47,923
Good night, Malcolm.

933
01:41:53,648 --> 01:41:55,424
Good night, sweetheart.

